Republican strategy to resist Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that election fraud cases in the United States are more rare than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, the lawyers of the Republicans counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is for sure: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing U.S. federal elections.
That is why most state governments have enacted laws since 2009 that make it difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 election, which brought the Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were passed in 2011 alone, restricting voting rights in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to show a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of expression of will and take away the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of a law passed in Indiana.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to show photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the age required to vote, do not have an ID card with a photo issued by their state’s government authority.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 percent of African Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 percent of citizens over the age of 65, and 20 percent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Students who vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their school in several states.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, which vote mostly for Republicans, to use for voting the certificates issued by these clubs.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship for voting.
This was the first time such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at restricting the voting of Latin American citizens.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Hispanic voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated legislation in 2011 to abolish voter registration on election day in eight states.
They have also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those who wish to register.
This restriction has not gone without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to add about 10 million citizens to the lists.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have resulted in a 17 per cent drop in the level of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the total number of voters in the state.
The same thing happened with Latin Americans.
Representing only 11% of voters, they constituted 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who formed 76% of voters, among early voters were only 46%.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring photo ID.
However, the new rules that have come into force will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics of the Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that were passed, seeing them as clearly aimed at influencing the results of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
