The Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, reports that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused a stir — and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, neither much nor little.
Furthermore, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the Standard Model—our best, or at least “least imperfect,” description of the nature and behavior of matter—but which was previously undetectable by experiment.
But physicists are still not entirely sure that it is the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although for full confidence some data is not yet enough.
Imagine, however, that we are talking about the Higgs boson, since the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and we will see what this means.
There is, in this world, one law which is absolutely inevitable, which says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way around this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise you will harm yourself.
But although the physics of elementary particles is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of a similar nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" lies, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
Therefore, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens, called fermions, who prudently obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, bosons, an abominable gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything — at least this principle, which means that they can calmly be in the same place at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratory's (by the way, quite extraordinary) Particle Adventure website, these bosons are, in turn, divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the "force particles", through which the main forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson in some way refers.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: the photon, or “particle of light”, which is the “courier” of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when one particle that has an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "violates" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, roughly like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "violation" an electromagnetic wave is born (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of the "force carriers".
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be “broken”.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could shake only a very large stone.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like the one operated at CERN – the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring 27 km in diameter! – is needed to achieve such enormous energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never keep itself on the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like a photon, by the way) do not.
So, what can all these studies “bring” to you, asks Ms. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to test the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to sense the discrepancy between the results of observations and the predictions of the SM.
In addition, some of them are eager for such a discrepancy to be discovered, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to "new physics" and shut some holes in the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms roughly 80% of the universe (oh-oh!).
But so far, no such differences have been found in CERN.
Implications
The benefits of these studies for the everyday life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that it does not exist.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell’s labs could not have imagined what a revolution their work would bring.
They anticipated their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that initially the laser was seen more as a “laboratory gadget.”
Imagine...
And in addition, the application can be found for the tools that accompany the study.
For example, the same Willyard Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, while not at all its original purpose, now serves as the “eye” for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
