Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for not fulfilling their request after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Home Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, patients are not susceptible to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we are not aware of these sufferings.
More and more often, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanized,” it means “I want to feel better.”
