There is nothing special in comparison with the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes Bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competing with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, like the “credits” used to promote a video game that are earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and handled by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously ledger holders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses, like an e-mail.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege to add this new line.
We are talking about the hashing phase of the file, that is, the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of cheating, the user very quickly (in less than ten minutes) would want to pay twice with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the prize is regularly split in half, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by one hundred million, which leaves another reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites that provide Bitcoin services have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen from reserves.
“The defect used does not concern the protocol itself,” assures Pierre Noiza, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes real money payments using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Major players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
The “giant sales” were announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Nouza, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which is thus cheaper.
The owner has better control over their personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by the phone, Pierre Noisy said, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“It will take some time before Bitcoin is established, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB’s report suggests, by the way, that the various risks considered elevated today should the system succeed.
