The Difficult Births of the Egyptian Constitution
This is a risky new move by President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever, on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it emergency powers, he has decided to play wa-bank.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
It is almost two years since Egypt has relied on a preliminary text that has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal contradictions.
This new initiative only strengthened the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his “autocratic nonsense”, continuing to “violate the word” and “violate the law”.
The camp of his followers believe that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis, speeding up the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time, which causes the Brothers to abandon the intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent rages across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote positively, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for accelerated voting is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I reserve myself extraordinary powers,” which are supposed to be completed after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted yesterday for the text.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to convey their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
To achieve the required quorum, 11 reserve participants were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that in most cases the articles were voted unanimously.
Commentators, by the way, amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around... time for prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was set incorrectly.
The text, which was voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of general attention, Article 2 eventually remained identical to the Article of the 1971 Constitution, which states that “the principles of the Shari’ah are the main source of law”.
Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace “principles” with “rules”, which would make it possible to apply them more strictly.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," replied the liberals, who saw it only as PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of Shariah laws.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomier, this is alarming because “people called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.”
We can observe the birth of theocracy.”
Many liberals are also agitated by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be far less moderate than the current one.
“There is currently no specific religious intervention.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulemas, but people with university education, some were trained in the French system,” said Alexis Bloe, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that “ambiguities may arise around Article 220, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, - ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to whether civil judges are competent to make decisions about this.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is criticized because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers claim that they have significantly decreased compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defense budget will be held not in the Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Also, the trial of civilians in military courts will not be prohibited, despite the requests of human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they consider detrimental to freedom.
Blasphemy remains the responsibility, and henceforth insults are prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles anymore talks about the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Moraef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will take to the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy places, the navel of the Earth and the sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comfort and the primordial nature.
AIF has identified five of the most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Let's go to the holy places
It is worth visiting the Jordan River, in which Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that everyone who enters this “bath” receives God’s grace.
And Galilee is the place of Jesus’ miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm, and filling the nets.
Here Jesus appeared to the disciples and after the resurrection.
But most of all the holy things in Jerusalem.
Believers here go through the Path of Sorrow or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (Latin - Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Praetorium - where the judgment was, and through the streets of the Old City leads to the Temple of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the Crucifixion, the Anointing Stone and the burial place of Jesus.
Here is the symbolic Christian Pup of the Earth, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was erected on the place where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which they made a cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the holiest place for Jews - the Wailing Wall, left over from the temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different confessions leave here notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Make a journey on the vertical
The ruins of the fortress of Massada remained from a secret shelter from enemies, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on steep cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And only those who are fond of mountaineering can get to them by their own path.
The rest to this historic peak is delivered by a lift on a cable car.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, which in the winter months - a huge influx of tourists.
A shuttle bus takes him from the foot of the mountain.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit the unique museums
There are about 300 museums in the country.
You don't get to see them all in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the oldest Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
You should also visit the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his exposition are widely presented paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cezanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akko, you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which is a few halls of ancient Turkish baths with masks of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth going to the unique private Rally Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no guides and souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are not accepted.
The fifth - the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells about one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section - the children's memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children destroyed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk into it, and you're in total darkness.
The stars are blinking.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Heal
Israel’s three main resort areas are located on the coasts of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, the Red Sea is bathed even in the winter months, since the water temperature there does not fall below 21 degrees of heat, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and they swim there all year round.
By the way, this most extraordinary sea in the world is located at the lowest point of the planet - at 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a brine that easily keeps afloat even those who do not know how to swim at all.
The scenery around here is incredibly beautiful.
Come here to undergo a course of treatment with salt water - rapa, and healing mud, and treat health with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes to put in order the shaken nerves.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
They are kept by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through it passed the famous Sea Route, connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to wander through the narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
They say if you touch the walls on the street "your" sign, Fortune will be favorable.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds coming from all over Israel and even other countries for a photo shoot.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can wander around the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the seat of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
the Tourist on the note
When going to Israel, do not worry about your imperfect English: in the country about 30% of the population know Russian.
It is better to take money on a trip not in euros, but in dollars, which are easy to exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar - 3.8 shekels).
Public transport is mostly buses, but there is a high-speed tram in Jerusalem, and in Haifa there is the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and connecting the Lower City with the Upper.
It's basically an underground funicular.
Travel in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can travel with transfers for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops, public transport stop working.
On Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels - only kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that combine milk with meat.
It offers a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts made with coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus paste, a variety of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falalel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israel.
But there are a lot of fed cats, which "walk on their own".
In the evening, they can be seen sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Ants love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Car rental, depending on the brand, will cost from $ 37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to 188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance, $15 a day.
A bicycle rental will cost 15 shekels. per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Numerical language
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most come to travel and rest citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
