Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in the following years took an active part in a number of projects of the Agency.
But the path to space Poland began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory the ideas from his groundbreaking work “Introduction to Cosmonautics”.
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after a few years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltri and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a well-known global space propagandist, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway track was built in Poland, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket was to be used to accelerate or brake the cart.
Information about this train is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The research was carried out by the Section of Armament Engineering in cooperation with Professors Mieczys<0xC5><0x82>aw Wolfke and Gustav Mok<0xC5><0xBC>ycki.
From the preserved materials it can be seen that the studies have reached the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, in a specialized press, the idea of a photoelectric fighter rocket, which was proposed by an engineer Rogozinsky, appeared, and the following year the work "Air Torpedo Rocket and Air Bomb Rocket" by Leliva-Kzhivoblotsky was published.
Both projects were developed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects for the military use of rocketry were carried out by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, the work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautychne).
For the first time about society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine "Problems", which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the fall of the POA became its full member.
The following year, Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902-1959), the first chairman of the POA, became deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile, capable of covering a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested on the Bled wasteland.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to engage in real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Institute of Aviation carried out the development of the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was able to bring a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then, versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Repeal of the public works law is not the solution to the problem.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The decision sparked a lively debate in the community.
It will certainly be interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberal-oriented economic systems in the EU, as well as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated economic competition.
In essence, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital along with unrestrained financial speculation.
As a result of a significant difference in the cost of labor (wages), price tension arises.
Under this concept, we need to understand the state when the producer, through the delivery of cheap goods, tries to withstand economic competition by “disrupting” the value of the competitor in order to take away most of the market and, thus, increase its own income.
On a massive scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either moving production abroad, or cheap purchases abroad, or disappearing. As a result, unemployment increases in those countries where the cost of labor, compared to others, is high.
Since private capital does not bear any social responsibility, including for the unemployment it produces, the inevitable expenses of the state for social needs grow.
In general, the situation reinforces the reluctance of employers to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the social and economic damage caused by their pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistical data.
Unceremonious methods of private capital create at the level of the economies of individual states situations when the governments of countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments surrender their own populations to private capital, despite social decline.
This is reflected primarily in changes in the current legislation.
The aim is to economically force its people to submit to the dictates of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
It acts as a system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment and at the same time serves as a tool for reducing the rights of workers in the field of labor legislation.
As a result, the level of poverty increases, and at the same time the gap between the poor and the rich increases.
In Germany, for several years, there has been a public distribution of food to the poor, who are unable to feed themselves with their own labor.
The number of these people is already approaching one million.
Within the framework of improving the competitiveness of the German economy, there are constantly cases when employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them extra to get a living wage.
Such a scandal became known to the public and in the case of additional employees of the Bundestag.
Economic measures in almost all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation in which people under the pressure of a catastrophic fall in social status are forced either to emigrate, as was the case in the 19th century, or to exist on a beggarly wage in the margins of society in the hope that private investment capital will one day come to the country.
But the question is, where will it come from?
If the capital comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, since a Chinese, a Hindu, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian, an African still works for a share of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media are sickeningly asserting that the state cannot participate in the capital of its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital persists in insisting that the state should not intervene in the economy by controlling actions.
The next question to be answered is whether private capital, which now practically governs politics and the state as a whole, is acting for its own selfish purposes?
The unequivocal answer is yes.
The proof is the existence of almost all-powerful and ubiquitous lobbies in all states.
As a result, we have a desperate situation, manifested in corruption, ensuring mutual benefits, in legislation, where almost everything deserves punishment, but is not a crime.
In Germany, the situation is such that government ministries, due to a lack of financial resources, entrust the development of draft laws to private law firms that are closely connected with industry.
Then these bills are approved by the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as the constitution of the Western type says, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
It is obvious that liberal-oriented democracy is now rapidly finding itself in a situation as described by Appian in The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Days of Caesar and Pompey: “The state has long since disintegrated, and agencies are engaged in violence.
Bribery, illegal taking of favors with stones and swords.
Bribery and corruption flourished without any prohibitions, and the people went to the elections with a pre-sold vote "... decent people did not run for the post of ruler at all, in the end one day the state itself was left without a consul for eight months. . . . "Seriously began to say that the only salvation in this terrible situation was the autocracy and the need to choose an energetic person ".
As in ancient times, modern society is dominated by its own reckless interests without taking into account public interests.
Private capital is no longer inherently intended for public use.
The current result is no different from the past: the unprecedented decline of the elite without any effort to carry out reforms of a deeper nature.
Hence the cause of fascist and communist regimes must be sought in the reckless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
To date, the absence of these regimes and the existence of a liberal democracy can be perceived as a certain pause, after which the next round is expected.
First of all, it is tragic that the current elite completely ignores the consequences of the hundreds of thousands of victims in the future, the humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already witnessing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know from old and new history.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, or at least not forever.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and national and European levels, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the participation of the state in the economy, strengthen the role of citizens in the governance of the state and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
