"Operation Argo": When there is nowhere worse, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student protesters seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the ousted Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution in the United States, which had been the patron saint of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, the positive outcome of the situation was not expected - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it could fundamentally undermine the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, to achieve the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was unable.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by an unsuccessful attempt to free the hostages by force.
The prisoners were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations mediated by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The defeat in Iran contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election, which culminated in the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, “Operation Argo” describes one episode of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six employees managed to escape.
After difficult journeys, they ended their journey at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, with the help of an extravagant cover legend, according to which they traveled on Canadian passports as members of the filming team, looking for a place in the country for filming a sci-fi epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, which was invented by “evacuation” expert Tony Mendes, demanded Hollywood’s cooperation.
In order for the legend to be true, specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, held press conferences, a fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation have long been kept secret, a film based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film-cinema opus", the story of a successful idea, a scam - an example can be a number of films about Ocean's friends.
The film constantly changes the mood - on the one hand, documentary scenes from Tehran (the credits show iconic historical photos of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightened Hollywood passages intersect with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then scenes from CIA headquarters and other agencies - men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of institutions, by phone ...
Ben Affleck has had a great career restart.
From a derided actor, he became a respected director, and his play ceased to be an object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third feature film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The City" (2010).
At the same time, this is the first Affleck film that is not shot in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place at the same time refers to the qualities that elevated the earlier films of the director above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck is showing it in Argo, where Tehran is playing Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, during the reconstruction of real events - the opening scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when somewhere suddenly the story changes.
Affleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters in a Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes something comes up - there it all does not work out so elegantly (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents the impending crisis at the airport of Tehran, and the chase on the runway look quite far-fetched).
The disadvantage of Argo is the distraction associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman in the role of Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film lacks a bit of drama, it’s a film that can be watched with moderate interest, valuing the staging and retro-style recreating the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to capture.
However, this is enough to remind of one, still in a certain sense of living history, as well as to testify to how exaggerated the idea of omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services.
