MVRDV architects prove that real adventures happen not only in the imagination - on the example of Speikenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
“To me, this building seems fun, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again,” says Lisette Verheig, passing on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, thinks, "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself: why do we need another library today?
Everyone has an Internet, an iPad, and e-books.
No one wants to go to a library like this anymore, right?
Spekenisse, a small bedroom town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesquely painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had the only way to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Vini Maas of Rotterdam’s MVRDV architectural bureau, a master of bold bar charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical buildings, approached the task with his usual equanimity and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the members of the jury looked around puzzled and shrugged, the bold Maas folded from his original gift a pyramid in size and ended the speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here it is, my proposal: "Book Mountain" in Speykeniss, the so-called Buchenberg!
Nine years later, this <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, Book Mountain was awarded the second prize of the “Best Library of the Netherlands 2012” competition.
The project also participates in the national Dutch competition of wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, a faceless suburb that previously had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, the white facades of which suggest the idea of a dairy, has become richer for one modern piece of architecture.
But most importantly - in Speykeniss appeared the first in the history of this town public building of cultural purpose.
The Long Road to a Book
First impression: book Eldorado under the cheese cap.
There is only one elevator in the center of the mountain range, because true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
The glazed room on all sides is bright and easily visible, the floors of burnt brick and elegant street lights unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is recreated perfectly.
Involuntarily looking for benches, dogs and playing football boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
“Usually, bookshelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless,” says Winnie Maas.
We put the classic configuration of the space on the head and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The interior space of the book mountain is used skillfully: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and technical premises.
Especially please black bookshelves, which serve as a wall decoration, then railings, then stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and construction engineers are lost in guesses, what kind of unknown material.
“We were committed to working with secondary materials,” explains Joppe Trauborst, project manager representing the Speikenisse community, as required by the standard.
And one day, at an agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we found a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, an artificial fibrous material of millimeter thickness is used as a substrate for the roots.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, after which it can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed into a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a little like a new car and a little sneaker.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Whoever overcomes the path of almost 500 meters in length will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wood ficuses in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and first of all about the proper humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
The cost of a new soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite the many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun only gets inside for a short time.
Wide farms of glued wood, located perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig was already here.
Cynthia Bogard, a teacher of traditional Chinese medicine, called Bukenberg “the soul of Speikenisse, which has been missing for a long time.”
The reason: a few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from their own collection.
These books were supposed to take up empty spaces on the shelves of a not yet fully stocked library – at that time it had 70,000 books.
The idea worked.
The regiments are forced to the top.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Vinnie Maas.
“I think thanks to our invitation now every resident is connected in some way to this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal problem, which in professional jargon is called identity creation.
Spiekenisse wrote his literary history.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
This is just the starting point for identity building.
Sabo: "The Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and Europe, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first made clear that it would vote against the Palestinians’ application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from the vote.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Now Germany needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not believe that she supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO made the offer.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, moving from the policy, which, so to speak, was controlled by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that the Europeans do not have a coherent single policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that while they are only finding their role, they are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
Such a foreign policy, which is carried out by France or Great Britain.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
This is a willingness to take a position in their national interests that does not depend on the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests differ greatly from those of other major states, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to offend the public and the elites in Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn’t put too much emphasis on that, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the United States by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the United States, the understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic a fiasco as it was in the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that she should be taken seriously as a player on the international arena and that her interests should be taken into account.
In Europe, there are differing views on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, strongly supported the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and its position as an important partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a single, consistent European policy, but this is not the case now.
They are therefore unable to take a broader approach and are forced to act instead on their own view of the situation.
This is what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This topic has always been sensitive.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they must play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really assume the leading role?
Or is the leading role still difficult to give to Germany?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings are manifested.
The Germans don't just deal with it.
Actually, it’s an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
