Through Twitter’s short news service, he accused Morsi’s supporters of wanting to lead a “putsch against democracy.”
“If he calls a referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him,” Yasser Saeed said.
“We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers is not yet avenged,” Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Khaled Ali as saying.
Many judges also said they did not want to observe the referendum, which would have made it invalid.
"The Koran is our Constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, in turn, called for the opposite demonstration, but, as a precaution, not in Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other bank of the Nile in front of Cairo University.
It was attended by a large number of women under veils and Salafi adherents who shouted: "The people demand the application of God's law."
They demanded from Morsi: "Clean up the country!" and assured: "The Koran is our constitution."
The struggle for power over the symbolic square on which it all began provoked a state of almost civil war.
Morsi’s followers clearly did not want to take that risk.
The Muslim Brotherhood said both opponents and supporters of the draft constitution had spoken out loud and clear.
Now is the time to let the people decide at the ballot box in which direction the country should go.
The majority for the Islamist project, it is considered a solved case.
“The concept of ‘human rights’ is never mentioned.”
Hafiz Abu Saeed is enraged by this forced constitutional process, which, in fact, was to last until February with the participation of all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were imprisoned or brought to justice under Mubarak.
Not because he shared their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, sentenced, arrested.
And now the words “human rights” are never found in the new constitution, he regrets in an interview with “Welt am Sonntag”.
The expansion of Morsi’s influence over all three branches of power in the state disappoints the lawyer.
These measures represent a clear blow to the democratic rules of the game and will lead the Egyptians to a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening the civilian state, the president de facto annulled it,” said Saeda.
Without civil society, democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels that everyone has left him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of the directions on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
There may be a reckoning for that.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: “You’re creating a monster you can’t control.”
Norwegian rakfisk: the worst smelling fish in the world?
Norway’s population of five million has one of the highest standards of living not only in Europe, but worldwide.
Perhaps the secret of the success of this country is somehow connected with the local addiction to one extremely catchy fish dish?
Take a few overripe pieces of cheese.
Put them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sports clothes.
Leave them there for a week.
You will get a bouncy smell of raspberries - one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies.
I'm in a small town called Fagernes, a three-hour drive from Oslo.
Around snow-covered picturesque views. It is very beautiful, but in the air spills an indestructible characteristic smell.
Rakfisk is a trout, sprinkled with salt and fermenting in water for up to a year, depending on what kind of soul you need to achieve.
As the twilight condenses and cools, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes dedicated to this very, shall we say, exciting dish.
"She is eaten raw and washed down with a glass of aquavit, the local dark vodka," explains Haward Halvarsen, a local firefighter by profession and part-time "rakfiskov general" who runs the festival.
All around us, people eat fish cut into small cubes and drink it in large portions of alcohol.
“Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk,” says Haward.
This drink is able to break the smell.
I'm trying a couple of pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - not much different from the portion of sushi that you took with you on the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from completely different times, times of poverty, when, even before the appearance of refrigerators, fish in the fall were soaked in hermetically sealed barrels with salt water.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish has already well and thoroughly fermented, it was extracted and, having muffled the perception of alcohol, eaten.
The last generation remembers the fact that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, who are attracted by jobs, high salaries and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (an old rival, and not so long ago and a much more prosperous neighbor) massively come here to work.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat ominous, element of Norway’s past.
It is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you <0xC2><0xA3>9 ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world’s news, and most of the country’s residents seem to be comfortable with that.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the terrorist attack is called “the incident of July 22.”
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peace-loving country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
At the heart of Norway’s prosperity today is the growth (since the early 1970s) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“Oil, however, is not the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our rakfiska tray-handler, a woman with long blond hair and strikingly blue eyes, the epitome of Nordic well-being.
We are a people, as you call it, reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she is fluent in English.
We don't like to show off, we're not boastful.
Norway is very careful with its oil – most of the revenues of the oil and gas industry are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was squandering money they didn’t have, Norway was conservatively calculating all costs.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
"And there is a raffle," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing in the snow in line for some food - I've had enough raffis.
Here's a hamburger with salmon meat - it's certainly exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
In my hotel there is a special dinner dedicated to the rakfisk, during which visitors vote to determine the best or, perhaps, the most fragrant fish.
There is a live TV show, which shows the presenter in a bow tie, surrounded by plates with raffis.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-J<0xC3><0xBC>rgen, what do you rate the best fish out there in the mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, here's our estimate."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls from a chair, perhaps taking over the aquavit.
Or maybe it was just the smell of fish.
Mexican President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto will have a difficult start to his career.
As Mexico’s newly elected President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country’s population.
Traffic in Mexico City is in a particularly bad state.
This city is overloaded with transport and at the best of times, and since Monday, steel barriers have been erected, cutting several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, will wear a presidential vest and take the reins of the country.
He faces a difficult task.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, who is now out of office, but the country is mired in a war on drugs that has claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
“My government declares to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,” Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the White House’s Oval Office earlier this week.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto’s political career, alongside the President of the United States, had developed as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the country's capital, opinions about the new leader are divided.
Straight-lined man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, he is remembered with warmth.
Residents credit it with the revival of tourism, the development of the resort area and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, which are strikingly different from the roads with potholes and pits that were previously on this site.
The plaques with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We have hopes for real and serious change with him,” says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman from the Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that our country so urgently needs, especially in the area of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI party was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
In addition, he refutes the accusations of lack of contention made by the opposition to the new president.
He is very forthright and very committed to the realization of his vision of the future of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, a man who knows how to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, is the most striking contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under the overpasses of highways, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also of a severe nature of this metropolis.
Troops had been deployed earlier this year to quell drug trafficking gangs in those areas; violence against women was particularly acute.
In the last two years alone, dozens of bodies of murdered women have been found in a wasteland near a vast landfill.
More than a thousand women were killed in Mexico State during Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto's governorate, far exceeding the figure in the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Juárez, which has become a household name when it comes to the murder of innocent women.
According to Mr. Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto ' s opponents, he could at best be said to have been unable to cope with the problem of killing women during his tenure as governor.
In the worst case, his administration is accused of completely ignoring this problem.
A resident of a concrete house similar to most homes in this dilapidated area, Irineja Buend<0xC3><0xAD>a has a hard time holding back tears by showing me photos of her late daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her roommate.
“When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before,” Ms. Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and her body was already numb.
Mariana’s mother retells this story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where he hangs next to the crucifix, on which there is only one word: justice.
That, they said, was what the family was denied.
“State officials treated me like an old gossip, a disgruntled troublemaker.
They want people to just accept everything they say and keep quiet.
But this is wrong, it cannot be done, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around,” she says.
Wearing the presidential garb on Saturday, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, along with her, will take on a difficult responsibility.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crimes, and the new president has promised to make addressing the issue a priority during his tenure.
“I hope he will be exactly the same president as he was governor,” says Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo of the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecution says.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's claims of poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning's stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions of detention were cruel.
The U.S. military has been accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified materials in U.S. history, did not take advantage of the many opportunities to file a complaint about the ill-treatment, which, according to him, he had to endure while in military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, the military prosecutor, Major Ashden Fein, said records of Manning's weekly visits by prison officials for nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of Manning's motion to dismiss, on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and sufficient punishment in themselves, took place the day after Manning had stated that, while in custody, he had intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the website of WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday’s hearing, Prosecutor Fein, along with Manning, reviewed reports that were filed after Manning’s visits by administration officials during his time in Quantico prison, where he was held under a strict detention regime from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he viewed the prison administration's treatment as "excellent" and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized."
The reports reviewed do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being asked directly about the conditions of his detention, Fein said.
Manning replied that he was verbally concerned about these problems and that the administration officials who visited him had discussed the problems with him and stated that they would deal with them, but had not recorded them in writing.
“They recorded ‘no problems’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t bring it up in the conversation,” Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his ill-treatment in January 2011 during a hearing of a commission examining suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he had wanted to have the “injury prevention” regime removed from him and the conditions of detention relaxed.
Military officials explained that the restricted detention regime — a level lower than the suicide-prevention surveillance regime — was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay, so they can cancel the injury prevention regime ... so that my standard of living improves, from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait and that he had once lost consciousness due to the intense heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not given to know how your fate is decided, and what is happening in the outside world.
“My world has shrunk to Camp Arifjan, the size of my prison,” Manning said on Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in this cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day — alone.
Manning says he was only allowed to leave a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleeping or even just lying in the daytime was forbidden by the rules.
According to Manning, during sleep, he was constantly struck by the light that penetrated the outside of the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he rolled over in bed at night, he said he was woken up and forced to turn on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning's misconduct in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, a judge questioned Manning about a statement he made while testifying on Thursday that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates at a morning checkup.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Responding to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should throw away a blanket he could cover himself with, but admitted that no one directly ordered him to throw it.
Manning said on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could have used a rubber band of shorts or flip-flops to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were taken from the cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to go through during his detention, and will significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is due to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to offer Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and to contest the other charges as excessive.
The resumption of the hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims Manning was held in Quantico under rules governing the detention of detainees with the strictest possible regime.
The charges against Manning include aiding and abetting the enemy, illegally facilitating the publication of data on the Internet, transmitting information related to national defense, and the theft of state property or documents.
If convicted on all counts in the indictment, he could face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of a Mexican-American.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarrette believes that Mexicans of American origin are torn between the two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals corridor, approached the border control zone, and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two queues: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called a Mexican all my life.
It’s just a casual name, like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later, I focused on the complex design of the “American of Mexican origin”.
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conventional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask or answer questions.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
So I got my American passport and lined up for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The agenda included the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto was willing to talk about the rise of the Mexican economy, thanks to which Mexicans will now be able to stay in Mexico with the same success, instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old grievance.
Most Americans never thought about the fact that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and at gunpoint forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only necessary for any U.S. statesman to say a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elite of Mexican society there are complaints that Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are full of militancy.
Mexico’s relationship with more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States is the most complicated.
Want to talk about insults?
That's enough.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone—father or grandfather—had no opportunity to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - dark, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
Mexico sees it differently.
Today, our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and got good jobs, but we do not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider as our own.
United States of America.
Besides, we know that the majority of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We respond to them in the same way.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as not real Mexicans.
We don’t speak Spanish well enough, and our ties to Mexico aren’t strong enough.
Our very existence for them is explained by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain now, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the U.S. as a child, and this reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican-Americans — Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Mexican-Americans are offended.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances of Mexican origin do not feel that they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations were not sufficiently complicated, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to serve as sort of ambassadors for Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It's not gonna work.
Too many insults in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still can’t forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated in Mexico recently.
Yeah, right.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
Ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be fragile foundation for further peace
Is a long-term peace possible between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
It sounds like the usual, pointless debate about who started first; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from Gaza fell in the vicinity of the Israeli capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, while Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly stuck in their perennial conflict, the Middle East has changed.
This can be treated in different ways, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have swirled in a rebellious storm many established realities, and the Palestinians with the Israelis have not managed to stay away from the vortex that shook the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give reason for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, is implemented, the clashes this week have only strengthened the positions of security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will say that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some leaders of the group were destroyed and 1.7 million residents blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time works for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
The resurgent regional leader, Turkey, once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, has come out in support of Hamas, followed by Qatar, one of the Gulf’s richest and fastest-growing states.
Hamas’s triumphant supporters claim to have created an Islamist crescent around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the militant group Hezbollah, to Syria, in which increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad, and further to Jordan, where the king’s power is threatened by Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where under President Mohamed Morsi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was ousted in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization largely similar to Hamas, and its leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic arrangements, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to opposite conclusions.
In the military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the Hamas-launched missiles.
Israeli citizens can sleep soundly, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the United States has remained true to its position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under the Binyamin Netanyahu government, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that approximately 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from Gaza since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part through a wall that enters the West Bank – a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian state – and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party – in preparation for the January 22nd elections – has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What's the point of pandering to the Palestinians and giving them a state of their own?
If they were to hand over all power in the West Bank, would they not launch rockets towards Israel from there, as their Gaza brothers do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and rigidly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will win; however, their calculations can be refuted by the Arab Spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere, do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be domestic problems.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on the cease-fire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel must also take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes in the Arab countries take place, depriving the Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repressions are already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect – the growth of the Arab population – only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the movement of Hamas are being paid for by the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need external momentum.
There remains the only solution to which sensible representatives on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, are relentlessly calling for: a two-state solution and Israeli cession of territories in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, that a ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long since made the decision to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, and Turkey and Qatar are in a better position than ever to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state that have been adopted since 1967, given the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming vote at the UN, which could result in recognition of Palestine’s virtual statehood.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never submitted his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still shows reluctance to engage with the problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on uniform packaging for cigarettes entered into force.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of diseased parts of the body contrastingly stand out on the dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first-ever Australian law on the same-type packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same box of dull olive color with creepy pictures of disease-stricken parts of the body and images of children whose health is undermined by smoking of their parents.
In addition to the various pictures and inscriptions warning of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs introduced is mandatory from this Saturday - the names of brands that are printed in the same small print.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for the registration of packages of tobacco products.
The Australian federal government says the aim of the measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving them of this bad habit of fashionable status.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26, in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
"It is obvious that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through the design of packaging," explains Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated in children with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest proportion of smokers in the world, so these changes will not affect the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market, which will sell cheap and affordable cigarettes.
“This law will have serious consequences different from those conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Counterfeit manufacturers from China and Indonesia will supply many more of these goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, claims that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone cases hiding unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (almost from scratch) since two months ago companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case to Australia in a high court.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesalers and expects a new batch.
This is good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among exactly the part of the population to which these measures are directed.
After the adoption in Australia of a number of laws that made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and their support for sports events, as well as prohibiting sellers to display cigarettes in a prominent place, advertising of tobacco products has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from placing ads on the network, but it cannot restrict overseas sites.
“If you’re a tobacco trader and you only have this small loophole left, the idea of promoting your product online would be extremely tempting,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of brand reviews written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is it really the work of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he did not spare his efforts and time and made a video, or is an advertising company behind it?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry has even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these States are making claims within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that the trade relations of all these countries with Australia are very small.
A WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the government discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar laws on packaging.
In 2001, Canada was the first country to make it mandatory to post smoking warning photos.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia demonstrably do not obey the innovations.
These pictures don't bother me.
I just don't pay attention.
“You just grab a cigarette and put the pack in your pocket,” explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yu, head of the King of the Pack tobacco store in central Sydney, says the same packaging has made it more difficult to stack the products on shelves.
“It used to take me an hour to unload a new batch, and now it takes me four hours,” he complains.
“The government had to take and completely ban cigarettes, we would then say: what to do, all right, it’s over, we’re closing the store,” he says, raising his hands up.
Boring in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport, because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced by another plane, which we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I won't lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books, nor magazines, nor iPhone, nor even duty-free shops will help much.
However, in recent years, more and more scientists and specialists in child development are in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations it is not so bad for us and for our children to be bored.
This causes the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Perhaps we should strive for boredom?
Yes, sir.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
Previously, I, like many, believed that boredom is an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
“In fact, boredom can boast a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls in Pompeii found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating back to the first century.
This leaves open the question of how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying research on this topic and asking a question to a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people "want to, but can not do what would bring them satisfaction."
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn’t do something they’d like to do.
I don’t want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing in experiencing boredom, he says, is “the disturbance of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is dragging on slowly.”
According to the description of boredom, it may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the surrounding world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when it’s really just hard to focus on something.
In their study, “Unemployed Mind: Defining Boredom in terms of Attention,” published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to a previously conducted experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading a journal.
Some participants also heard the loud sounds of an off-the-shelf television program included in the next room, others heard the same sounds at low volume so that they could barely be disassembled, and the third group listened only to voice recording without an extraneous soundtrack.
Those participants who heard the TV at a low volume level noted that they were bored, more often than others - they found it difficult to concentrate, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, the interruption of attention can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, “for example, peering into the flow of products on a conveyor belt in search of marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom.”
It is believed that when people start swinging on a chair or drawing doodles on a piece of paper, they do it from boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions simply help not to relax physically.
"The study showed that children who are not forbidden to erase and turn around learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we all get bored: with a flight delay (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show varying degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual characteristics, the researchers developed a special “boredom scale”.
Questions and statements such as "A lot of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I'm too interested, so there's not enough time for anything" are used to determine the score on such a scale.
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys are more likely to miss girls, says Steven Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially in the presence of a variety of external stimuli.
However, in general, adolescents in general are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted with the help of a pager almost 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
The results were as follows: 32% of teenagers said they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data on boredom would be like now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “adolescence has a peak of boredom,” mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Back to my original question: Is boredom useful?
Sometimes it doesn’t, because in extreme cases, research shows it can push people into absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling, or substance abuse in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has devoted more than two decades to the study of this problem.
“So our brains tell us to do something else; it’s boring,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this very brain does not always know what to do better.
If you get bored and you direct that energy to playing guitar or cooking experiences, you’ll make yourself better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop being bored, but he will not learn to deal with boredom on his own or in any other way to manage his time and work, - says Professor Fenske.
“Such self-regulatory skills are used in a variety of situations,” he says.
Your child learns not only to occupy himself with something, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think boredom should be celebrated.
However, to consider it something bad is also not worth it.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside of the continuous flow of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
“We see it in the way that we need to be bored more often, even though boredom is an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In the modern world, we are used to constant over-stimulation of the senses,” he says, “and when silence comes, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
It is not yet clear how the new law on the legalization of marijuana in the state of Colorado will be applied
Anthony Orosco, a 19-year-old football team player and a public college student in southeastern Colorado, is charged with a criminal offense that will soon be perfectly legal across the state: possession of a small portion of marijuana and the tube in which he smoked it.
Mr. Orosco says that he and friends were in Lamar one September and were driving in a car on the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer discovered marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco was subpoenaed for possession of drugs and possession of a drug-using device — minor offenses for which a fine of $100 is due — and a court date was set.
“We are being treated like criminals,” Mr. Orosco says.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that continues for weeks after the state of Colorado voted to legalize the use of marijuana in small amounts for entertainment, the decision of hundreds of small court cases depends not so much on the law, but on the place of consideration.
Charges of minor marijuana offenses are already being dropped in hundreds of cases here and in the state of Washington, which has taken similar action.
Police stations have already stopped bringing charges against people aged 21 and older for possession of small doses, which will be considered legal once the law takes effect in a couple of weeks.
However, in the more conservative counties of Colorado, prosecutors have decided to look into existing marijuana cases and continue to prosecute possession of the drug.
At the same time, in some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous areas of the West, they vote to prevent the emergence of new, state-licensed marijuana stores in their places.
“It’s going so fast that I don’t even know what to expect next,” said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
Representatives of the regulatory authorities in the state of Washington are also puzzled by scratching their heads.
They have to form rules to determine the procedure for licensing the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done before December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or for worse, is ahead of most other states in regulating marijuana use, first for medical purposes and now for entertainment.
“Colorado has a more orderly market, so they’re going to set a good example,” said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Alcohol Regulatory Board in Washington state.
But now no one can do more, admits Mr. Smith, than to put forward some proposals and hope that it will work.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we could be guided by,” he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will go into effect on December 6 and will put the state into a state of uncertainty for a year, when the state licensing system does not yet exist, and the right to own marijuana has already been legalized.
And there are still difficult technical aspects that need to be addressed in this period, for example, how to find a balance between the state's order on "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on its trade at a distance of 1000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
“It will be particularly difficult to locate licensed marijuana businesses in cities, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly formed marijuana legalization center research group.
On November 21, Aurora Police Chief Oates emailed his subordinates that the city's attorney's office would no longer hold anyone under the age of 21 accountable for possession of a small amount of marijuana, and that the police would stop incriminating people in these violations "from now on."
Police Chief Oates said police would monitor compliance with the city’s rules governing medical marijuana growers and prosecute illegal drug traffickers and distributors.
The Weld County District Attorney in northern Colorado, Ken Buck, presents a more rigorous approach to the matter.
After the vote on the bill, he said the prosecutor's office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession, mainly to encourage marijuana users to undergo treatment.
At the moment, 119 people are charged with possession of two or fewer ounces of marijuana, although many of them are accused of other violations.
“It is the duty of our institution to prosecute for acts that are considered criminal at the time of their commission,” Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The reaction was mixed even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected a proposal to legalize marijuana.
The police of Grand Junction, the largest city in the district, no longer prosecute adults for possession of a small amount of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported the decision, but also decided not to drop the charges in the already open cases related to the possession of marijuana.
“I believe it is our direct responsibility to enforce the law until it changes,” he said.
Despite the fact that 55% of Colorado residents who took part in the vote supported this decision, the inclusion of the use of marijuana for entertainment in the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the controversial reaction of residents in different parts of the state exposed the ambiguity of the attitude of local authorities to the state's experiment with marijuana.
“There’s a cultural barrier for district attorneys on this issue,” said Sean McAllister, a Denver-based attorney representing marijuana offenders and a local representative for the National Marijuana Reform Organization.
“They’ve been harassing people for so long that now they can’t really accept that it’s not a crime anymore,” he says.
Colorado and Washington, the first states to treat a small amount of marijuana the same as alcohol, are destined to become an experimental field nationwide to test the very idea of drug legalization.
Proponents of legalization and state officials plan to expand the territory of legalized trade, but at the same time they are cautiously waiting for instructions from the federal authorities, who still plan to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as a federal crime.
Supporters of marijuana legalization hope that the Justice Department will give in to this issue.
Despite several high-profile arrests of drug dealers and patients for medical reasons, the federal government has largely given the go-ahead for the medical marijuana trade in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
DEA agents are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, according to Kevin A. Sabeth, a former anti-drug adviser in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for the actions of the federal authorities.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations approved a moratorium on the opening of new marijuana stores, which could not have opened earlier than a year later.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, put forward a six-month ban on the marijuana trade, which is likely to be approved next week.
“We don’t want to be in a position where we’re going to give someone a license, and then it’s going to cause serious problems at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
The city voted against the amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still a lot of unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I survived Oxford for being a conservative.
Persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I have always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, a modern analogue of the ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization - freethinking and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying at the history department of Oxford University’s Worcester College in the late 1980s, I packed my bags and left, which resulted in the first real scandal in my life.
My father couldn’t stand it and cried.
Friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn’t like my classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I left because I had to drink from the rattled cups.
It wasn't really that much fun.
I ran away.
Yeah, I ran away because I was being systematically harassed and intimidated.
Not at all because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I studied in a private school.
I was poisoned for only one reason, and in this illustrious cradle of enlightenment, it looked like barbarism and blind bigotry: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was myself a supporter of the Conservatives.
You might ask, why think about it now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students who adhere to center-right views is subjected to the same harassment.
This institutionalized and ever-growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as the one granted to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at Corpus Christi College's student club in Cambridge say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and made to feel unwanted by guests" because of their political views.
They want to introduce an additional representative to the college’s Equal Rights Committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only exacerbated by a recent BBC 2 documentary on student politics, Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right, in which conservatives were portrayed as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cook, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association, riding in a Rolls Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with a silver canopy.
In other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made “scapegoats due to higher tuition fees.”
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the University of Nottingham’s Conservative Association, said in an interview with a Sunday newspaper that “there is an increasing left-wing bias in the university environment.
People who don’t even know us think we’re brazen and reckless children of rich parents.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, a student in the history department of Corpus Christi College, where a request for enhanced protection was filed, called the atmosphere “uncomfortable,” and Stephanie Cherill, 19, the new president of the Oxford University Conservatives Association, said the student club’s attitude to right-wing centrists had deteriorated significantly.
“This poses a threat both to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and to the normal lives of the club members,” she says.
The first few weeks at Oxford I was not just in the minority, I was alone.
I went there in September 1986, a timid and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford was plagued by hatred for the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university had voted to deprive former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree due to a reduction in budget allocations for higher education.
In such an atmosphere, even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable.
In the first days of the freshman week, when students get to know each other and the teachers, I felt for the first time what was waiting for me in front.
I did not know that the teachers not only looked through their fingers at the bullying of conservative students, but also took part in it with pleasure.
Political issues – the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s opposition to sanctions against the apartheid government in South Africa – have penetrated the wood-paneled walls of the auditoriums.
At my first seminar, I had to translate an eighteenth-century French text into English, and I was not ready for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the teacher, now the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
The text was difficult for me, I stopped.
Harry Pitt was a very gallant man with a face that looked like a cake.
“Thatcherists don’t teach French in principle, or do they just lack brains?” he asked.
The other students shrugged.
There were tears in my eyes.
“I advise you to take a few initial French lessons in your spare time, unless you’re, of course, very busy spinning around in society,” Pitt said.
I went back to my room very unhappy.
That night in college, I was sitting alone at lunch; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year student from the Faculty of English, who introduced himself as a member of the University's Conservative Association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
- Unfortunately, the situation is as follows:
Anyone suspected of being sympathetic to conservatives will be mocked.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be harder for you.
Most first-year Conservatives pretend to be Labour.
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to be a hypocrite.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick didn't work.
A freshman from the Faculty of Philosophy, Politics and Economics, who studied at Eton himself, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contagious.”
Other students echoed his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
"How do conservatives have sex?" one of them asked.
- They're banging each other, aren't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before criminal prosecution was abolished in the sixties.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or will I have to meet with like-minded people only under the cover of night?
Will I be forced to become a Labour MP and hide my true beliefs?
The three years that lay ahead of me began to seem like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only teacher in my college who did not hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for being Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He barely showed up in college.
He despised him for his provinciality, pettiness, and commitment to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he took up a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You won’t be happy here,” he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parents’ home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and impartial friends in the capital.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the forties, any political views were adopted there.
"But it's the best university in the world," he said sadly.
- They can't do that, except in the city of sleeping spires...
Even my communist friends have always behaved impeccably.”
His wet eyes darkened.
“Don’t make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You'll break my heart if you drop out of college."
I was exhausted by the constant trips to London and my emotional protection weakened.
My friend, also a conservative, could not stand the pressure and gave up his beliefs.
The following week, during a seminar, when another history teacher called me “the enemy of the people” very seriously, I decided to do the same.
In my soul, burned with shame, I admitted that "my parents brainwashed me," and called them "old fools."
The respite was short-lived.
The last nail in the coffin of my career at Oxford was destined to be hammered by my father.
At the time, he was writing two columns each week for Rupert Murdoch's publications.
My door was locked.
I did not go out, and five minutes later my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a crybaby and a rag.
But at the age of eighteen, no one should become the object of such anger and intimidation in an educational institution.
The saddest thing is that it was Oxford, which not only released fourteen Tory prime ministers, but to this day hides behind an undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and freethinking.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
About the exhibition "Valentino: master of sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornewitz and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of Valentino: Master of Sewing, a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high-fashion dresses created by his “home” over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is "il Signore" Garavani, but it could not have been written without his illustrious clients.
Valentino always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of the nobility.
The first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, abounds with personal letters and photographs signed by the most eminent aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowden, including Marie Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from the humble tailor from the town of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international “elite”.
Being in love with the royal court is not a bad thing.
“They at least don’t put out their cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet, like some beautiful pop stars do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornewitz.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an unparalleled host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
“We all loved coming to his chalet in Gstaad,” explains Heini’s ex-wife Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to fame.
And yet, he is a star.
Valeria Macca, representing Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza recalls a charismatic fashion designer.
