The hardest profession in the world: miners from Kawah Ijena
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk life and health, dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano on steep rocky trails
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living mining sulfur in the volcano Kawah-Ijen, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where sulfurous gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes upon contact with air.
Slitting huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, rolls the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up a rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, whose height is 2,386 meters, only 250 meters, but exhausted loaders need more than 40 minutes to climb the turtle step, hardly keeping balance and carefully groping the road, so as not to stumble and fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to a tourist from France, who fell a few years ago from the cliffs of Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur they mine
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists who photograph them, as if they were monkeys from the circus and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales, which the mining company located just above, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
It is about PT Kandi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, better to say, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
Then it sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical industries, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
“Since carrying 70 kilograms is the norm, we earn about 46,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.8) for each walk,” explains Anto, who usually performs three daily transfers.
He spends three hours on each of them and in the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
While this seems like a miser for such an inhuman effort, it is three times more than what he would have earned in the field.
"The daily fee for miners is very high by local standards, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the loader, who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not that heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as crushing as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where only Hindus, and brought her to Islam to take her to Java."
Anto has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly, and his eyes water because of toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years at risk in Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly, and his eyes drool because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
This is the price you have to pay to achieve your dreams.
“I’ll work another two years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished with life, this nice and smart young man could be a tour guide, waiter or porter at a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, lighting his way with a small lantern connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters drag baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company did not mechanize the extraction of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such deprivations.
In fact, they don’t even receive a portion of the 30,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.5) photo fee, which, along with the entrance ticket for 15,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.2), is charged by the guards of this reserve to tourists who come to take pictures of the volcano and its people-mules.
“It’s a job for cattle, not people,” says Badrusin, a 42-year-old root-carrier who has spent three decades in Kawah Ijen since leaving college.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will endure the work "as much as he can" because he needs money for the education of his three children aged 18 to 10 years.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because a volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur burns their throats and burns their eyes, when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in the dense columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that no one complains of their severe diseases ... more serious, obviously, than their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and ulcers under the shoulders.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unaynik can now only lift 50 kilograms in his 53 years.
Every day, he and his comrades haul 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, covering a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among thickets.
“I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here because a volcano is my whole life,” Unanik says, opening his mouth wide, missing a few teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult occupations in the world: what the human mullahs of Kawah Ijena are doing.
