UNASUR Summit Ends Without Promulgation of Lima Declaration
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, which was announced earlier and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the home page that it would be handed over after closure, but then confirmed that it would be published on the Peruvian Government website at some point.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the contents had been laid out by the President of Peru, Ollanta Umala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to information about the Summit was limited at all times.
During the day, a video of the presidential assembly without a sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "closed meeting, sound is prohibited."
A little information circulated among the reporters was conveyed by the spokespersons of some UNASUR Governments present at the meeting, but not in Peruvian.
The only document circulated during the day was a list of participating presidents, sparking outrage from hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the administration of the President of Peru sent an electronic message to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but this is a statement of Umala, and not an official document, which ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and at that time, despite the insistence of the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was also not circulated.
On the official ASPA website, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to ensure that transmission systems for all journalists are in place, but have limited the flow of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the ruling of the International Court of Justice, which begins hearing statements from both sides in The Hague on Monday, as part of the indictment Lima filed against Santiago.
“We will abide by and enforce a decision that clarifies the differences we are currently submitting to this international court,” Umala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of differences, pacts and international tribunals,” Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era added, and welcomed Umala with a handshake against the background of the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the International Court of Justice came just after Colombia protested this week the Bogota Pact, under which it recognized submission to the verdicts of that international court following its decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered wrong.
The summit was held in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Umala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects among South American countries had been approved, the amount of the proposed investment was $ 17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take “important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residency agreements.”
He said that action was being taken to improve “cooperation against citizen uncertainty and organized transnational crime, action to increase the availability of medicines, affordable Internet access in all corners of South America and to take into account the risks of natural disasters in a comprehensive and effective manner.”
As Europe is in crisis, “economic unification [of Latin America] should not have a triumphant foundation, but should serve to expand our productive foundation and envision a better future for our cities,” Umala added.
“We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes,” the Peruvian president said in a read-out message.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five are Peru-related and are limited to transverse axes in its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide further details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to rejoin the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, to be united and to have good relations between neighbours, was another theme highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before embarking on the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico City on Saturday to hold respectful talks on the maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of an international court challenged by Bogotá.
"The day after tomorrow (Saturday), I may meet with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
“We will review all these paths, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require a discussion with Nicaragua,” he said.
“With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
