Given the ratification by the United States Court of Appeals of a decision that nullifies the Vitro Group’s debt restructuring achieved through competitive bidding in Mexico, the scenario sets a fatal precedent for any national company with branches in a neighboring country that has solvency problems.
It seems that the procedures in support of the survival of firms that are allowed by Mexican laws are not valid in the country of the stripes and stars, contrary to international agreements.
In practical terms, the approval of Judge Harlin Hale’s June 15 ruling in the Bankruptcy Court of the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican firms defenseless in the face of the possibility of arresting their property on the other side of the Rio Grande.
However, the ruling opens the door to a leading glass producer in Mexico to appeal to the United States Supreme Court, citing three inconsistencies.
As an introduction, while the judge of the case notes that creditors must be governed by the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, located in New Orleans, says the main proceedings concern bankruptcy proceedings pending in Mexico.
The first paragraph implies the cancellation of international judicial cooperation in cases of insolvency of enterprises of a transnational profile.
In fact, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law on the Unification of International Trade Law was created, defining the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Second, the verdict states that without the inter-firm vote, recognized in the critical mass of the bankruptcy debt that Vitro had before the parent company branches, the majority necessary to approve the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro was not the first time this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, among them Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intercompany debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Competitive Proceedings.
It is also true that, by subtracting the votes of the branches, Vitro’s creditors, who fought against him in the courts of the United States, namely vulture funds like Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergenceia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached the majority.
The vote would be 45 per cent against 37 per cent.
These data are omitted by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, he accuses Vitro of the difficult situation it has faced since 2008, affected by the serious economic crisis that has overtaken the United States by striking the country.
In the meantime, the Gonzalez Sada family firm will appeal the decision to the Court of Appeal itself, so that the vote reaches its plenary, that is, five judges, given that only three voted.
In the event of failure, an application for a certificate will be filed, which will require a review of the process by the highest court, in this case the United States Supreme Court.
Worst of all, the court rejected a document sent by the Mexican government in the role of amicus curiae (“friend of the court”), which describes the process Vitro follows under the Bankruptcy Act, signaling that it is exempting itself from complying with agreements signed by both countries to link it to Article 15 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, it is noted that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, that is, the rules established for cases of interstate insolvency, which guarantee equal rights for debtors and creditors.
A carom from two sides: they hit Vitro and hit the country.
