Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
An avid basketball traveler Hector "Hetin" Reyes was more than 60 years associated with this sport and, thanks to him, traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico remember as many basketball stories as Hector "Hettin" Reyes.
Before a brain hemorrhage confined him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, as a small-scale player, a Major League basketball player, a BSN commissioner and head of the Bayamon Cowboys, and the president of the Basketball Federation.
“I’ve played many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at once, like when I was president of BSN, CEO of the National Team and president of the federation in the 90s,” Reyes recalls during a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayamon, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
“Basketball was my life.
Reyes does not exaggerate by making this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia collected over his long journey, testify to this.
Bayamon in the Heart
With the greatest emotions he keeps those who remember his way through the Cowboys, from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he turned 15 years of his performance as a co-agent or contract agent.
“These have been my best years, which I enjoyed the most because I’ve had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboys championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or manager.
There were many years of joy, including five championships that took place from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincey’s BSN debut.
From that moment on, Cuco Ortiz, who was a great administrator, became the leader,” Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was on his way here and was at the University of Alabama, Birmingham, telling me, "I have a very strong player for you, 6'7".
"Do you?"
And that was the beginning of Minsi, one of the best players that Puerto Rico had.
Bartow then recommended sniper Raymond Gauss, who was granted citizenship and became one of our top scorers.
I remember saying that if Minsi had brought the championship to Bayamon, Gauss would have helped win another one.
I enjoyed the Cowboys championship with Gauss, but already at a distance, because by 1988 I was already listed as the head of the federation.
By that time, I preferred to enjoy his achievements and Minnie’s achievements in the national team.
I remember the first time we won the U.S. at the Olympic Qualifying Tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we got fourth place and it had to be bronze if not for the Canadian referee who forced us to replay the final game, Reyes said.
Is that team from the 1990 World Cup the best team you've ever seen?
She is among the best, as well as the one who won from the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the one from the Pan-American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and beat the U.S. team, which was pretty similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
Not only did Mincey, Gauss, Ram<0xC3><0xB3>n Rivas, Fico L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, and Piculina (Ortiz), but also the young (Havier) To<0xC3><0xB1>ito Col<0xC3><0xB3>n and James Carter, the brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario 'Kihote' Morales, who was unable to participate in the 90s due to a knee injury.
The team, which may not have been the best in terms of personnel, but brought us a gold medal and great joy, was the team of the 1995 Olympic Qualifying Tournament in Neuquen, Argentina.
With role players like ‘Kanito’ Nieves, Pablo Alyce and young Rolando Hurruitner replaced by players temporarily suspended for disorderly conduct in the Mar del Plata Pan American Championship, we won gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Piculin Ortiz.
His performances in international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico dominated at this level the way Pikulin did.
And that doesn’t take into account his career in the different leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's a very difficult question.
We had a very good young man, including Julio Toro, Flora Melendez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
From a young age, I really like the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your greatest achievement in the Federation?
Participation in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 90s BSN had up to 17 teams per season.
What do you have left to do?
There were things I wanted to implement, such as regionalization of smaller categories.
For example, let the boys from Ponce play only in their field and only against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Now the guys travel and play too much, and it's unnecessary.
At the very least, I see the fruits of mandatory certification and coursework for managers, officials and judges.
It gives me pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Most of all, I listen to music, watch music videos of my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball matches.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the Dallas television series, in which he portrayed a businessman without principles, evil and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new Dallas season, died Friday night from complications caused by cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the Dallas-based production studio.
“Larry has returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role he most enjoyed,” his family said in a statement.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him at the Dallas Thanksgiving Fair.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and sequel, was next to Hagman when he died at Dallas Hospital, her rep said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original personality and lived a full life,” Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a liver transplant.
Long before "Dallas", Hagman had gained notoriety on television for his role as a decent guy in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie", broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he plays Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is changed when he meets an attractive genie girl played by Barbara Eden and begins to live with her under one roof.
He was also the main character in two comedies that rarely aired, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His work in film included well-received roles in The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully repulsive J.R. that brought Hagman to the top of his glory.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its entourage aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan “Who Shot J.R.?”, conceived to create hype around the episode, full of emotions in which Hagman’s character is almost killed, gave rise to international discussions and millions of dollars at risk in bookmakers.
It also helped to attract a record audience to the series at that time.
When the answer was given in the November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers watched it and turned Dallas into the second most watched entertainment program in history, after the finale of MASH in 1983, which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. stopped her and then threatened to charge her with prostitution if she didn't get out of town, but others also had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: an dishonest businessman and an unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), put on treatment.
“I know what should be on J.R.’s gravestone,” Hagman said in 1988.
It must be said, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
It's the only deal he's ever lost.
Victoria Principal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled on Friday Hagman as someone "huge, both on and off the screen."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us who are lucky enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new release of "Dallas" were shown a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
Five episodes of the second season have already been recorded and the sixth was in production, the channel reported.
Warner or TNT have not yet made a statement about what will happen to the series after Hagman's departure.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who shone in such classic works as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on the stage in New York in the early 1950s, and then served in the British Air Force from 1952 to 1956.
While there, he met the young Swedish artist Mai Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and they lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities live.
In 2001, he titled his memoir "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
“I didn’t include anything that I thought was capable of hurting anyone or affecting them in any way,” he told Prensa Asociada at the time.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in the hospital to help patients experiencing fear.
“I give them advice, I give them courage, I meet them when they go into surgery, and after,” he said in 1996.
I'm trying to offer some consolation, like "don't be afraid, it'll be a little uncomfortable for a short time, but you'll be fine."
He also actively opposed smoking and participated in several campaigns.
Begins a course that explores "The End of the World"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic phenomena such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Sharme decided to read a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible lure: the end of the “long countdown” of the Mayan calendar, December 21, which many people seized on as proof that the end of the world was coming.
But Sharma had no idea what was coming in the next couple of months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the financial crisis that some call the “long Armageddon,” and the growing conflict that Israel will be drawn into, a place where end-time Christian theorists believe the apocalypse will begin.
“I didn’t realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester of all,” Sharme told Rutgers-Camden University students this week.
If you analyze what is happening in the world at the moment, as if we only have 30 days left, it was a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those who have an apocalyptic mindset.
And he’s not the only professor to offer “end of the world” courses this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, Associate Professor Barry Wacker teaches a course in Media, Culture, and the End of the World.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
“We’re analyzing why these ideas spread over time,” he said, and the way in which hypothetical scenarios that trigger certain human actions are proposed.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war can break out.
This month, students analyzed films on apocalyptic themes and studied how they relate to real-life examples.
“I tried to tell the students what was probably plausible and impossible,” Wacker said.
On the main campus of the University of Pennsylvania, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of art history and anthropology, have teamed up to read a course called simply “The End of the World.”
"We're not adding '2012' to always be able to read the course again in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the “inevitable destruction,” students must study, prepare projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work “until the very night the world supposedly ends,” Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
“The places ended in two hours,” Restall said of his course for high-middle-class students, which was attended by 35 students.
We received emails for many weeks before the semester began from people who asked if there were any more places.
Students, in turn, assure that this course is one of the most interesting.
“I like to watch what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridged Robinson, a 23-year-old student in the Department of Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
And the apocalyptic way of thinking, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or lack thereof.
Will Vekesa, a 25-year-old student in the Department of Psychology and Nursing, said he watched all the apocalyptic movies.
“I’ve never heard of a course that would teach this,” he said.
I like him.
But none of the students interviewed — not to mention the professor — said they believed in the end-of-the-world date of December 21.
“Our first project affected the Mayan prophecy, and in some ways we discredited it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple University in West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key moment in the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic concern in Western culture that goes back several centuries, where people react to the changes around them, predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused an increase in these speculations.
“In other places, people don’t think about it,” he said.
Primarily in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered a question about whether he knew of any course about the “end of the world” there.
“The Philippines is not taking part in the end of the world,” he wrote, alluding to an order from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that many days of the last trial had long been talked about, and said that if nothing happened on December 21st, “people would immediately start thinking about the next date” or philosophizing that December 21st was the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world would end.
Students and teachers are very cautious about this date.
Some said they were going to end-of-the-world parties.
“Maybe I’ll call one of my friends and have a laugh,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
